04370nam a22007215i 9789048521890DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20142014ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485218907 a10.1515/97890485218902doi  a(DE-B1597)565877  a(OCoLC)1157061177  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aART0570002bisacsh04a791.4302330921 aCowan, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWalter Ruttmann and the Cinema of Multiplicity :bAvant-Garde Film - Advertising - Modernity /cMichael Cowan. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (260 p.) :b96 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFilm Culture in Transition00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Avant-Garde, Advertising and the Managing of Multiplicity -- t1. Absolute Advertising: Abstraction and Figuration in Ruttmann's Animated Product Advertisements (1922-1927) -- t2. The Cross-Section: Images of the World and Contingency Management in Ruttmann's Montage Films of the Late 1920s (1927-1929) -- t3. Statistics and Biopolitics: Conceiving the National Body in Ruttmann's Hygiene Films (1930-1933) -- t4. "Überall Stahl": Forming the New Nation in Ruttmann's Steel and Armament Films (1934-1940) -- tAfterword: Of Good and Bad Objects -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tFilmography -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Film Titles -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA key figure in early avant-garde cinema, Walter Ruttmann was a pioneer of experimental animation and the creative force behind one of the silent era's most celebrated montage films, Berlin: Symphony of a Great City. Yet even as he was making experimental films, Ruttmann had a day job. He worked regularly in advertising -and he would go on to make industrial films, medical films, and even Nazi propaganda films. Michael Cowan offers here the first study of Ruttmann in English, not only shedding light on his commercial, industrial, and propaganda work, but also rethinking his significance in light of recent transformations in film studies. Cowan brilliantly teases out the linkages between the avant-garde and industrial society in the early twentieth century, showing how Ruttmann's films incorporated and enacted strategies for managing the multiplicities of mass society.This book has won the Willy Haas Award 2014 for its outstanding contribution to the study of German cinema.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aExperimental filmszGermanyxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion picture producers and directorszGermanyy20th century. 4aFilm Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh  aGerman Studies.  aWeimar.  afilWalter Ruttmann.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311070065740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048521890zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048521890423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789048521890.jpg  a978-3-11-070065-7  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK